@startuml cert-lifecycles
' The Agent serving cert and the AgentTask client cert share one 6-step lifecycle; the deltas are the subject.
' Source of truth: docs/src/security/tls.md
!include _style.puml

' Manual line breaks below are deliberate; keep both limits above the longest
' hand-broken line so PlantUML does not re-wrap them into ragged text.
skinparam wrapWidth 420
skinparam maxMessageSize 340

participant "**AgentReconciler**\n**AgentTaskReconciler**" as R #87CEEB
participant "cert-manager\n(kaalm-ca-issuer)" as CM #F5F5F5
participant "**Agent** Pod" as AP #E6E6FA
participant "**AgentTask** Pod" as TP #E6E6FA
participant "**Gateway**" as GW #90EE90

note over R, GW #FFF8DC
  Both certs run the same six steps: same issuer, same mount
  path, same rotation mechanism, same ownerRef-driven teardown.
  Four things differ, and every one of them follows from a
  single fact: **an Agent has a Service and is a delivery target;**
  **an AgentTask has neither.**
end note

== 1. Created ==

note over R, CM #FFF8DC
  Both reconcilers create a Certificate named {workload}-tls in the
  workload's **own** namespace, owner-referenced to the workload, with
  issuerRef: { name: kaalm-ca-issuer, kind: ClusterIssuer }.
  Only the SAN shape and the usages differ:
end note
R -> CM : **{name}-tls** (per Agent)\nSAN: {name}.{namespace}.svc.cluster.local,\n.svc, {name}.{namespace}\nusages: **server auth + client auth**\n(one cert, both directions)
R -> CM : **{taskName}-tls** (per AgentTask)\nSAN: **{taskName}.{namespace}.task.kaalm.io**\na single entry, non-Service shape,\nbecause tasks have no Service\nusages: **client auth only**

== 2. Stored ==

CM -> CM : issue, then write the output Secret\n(name = Certificate.spec.secretName) into\nthe workload's own namespace, e.g.\nteam-support/support-assistant-tls

== Ready-gate: no Pod until the Certificate is Ready ==

loop until Certificate.status.conditions[type=Ready] is True
  R -> CM : read the Ready condition
  R -> R : **requeue**, do not create the Pod
end
note over R, CM #FFF8DC
  Identical on both paths. Gating Pod creation on issuance is
  what stops a Pod hanging on a missing projected Secret.
end note
R -> AP : create the Agent Pod
R -> TP : create the AgentTask Pod

== 3. Mounted ==

CM -> AP : /var/run/kaalm/tls.crt + tls.key
CM -> TP : /var/run/kaalm/tls.crt + tls.key
note over AP #E6E6FA
  **Has a listener.** Serves HTTPS
  with this cert, and presents the
  same cert as a client cert on
  agent to gateway calls.
end note
note over TP #E6E6FA
  **No listener.** Presents the cert on
  every call to $KAALM_GATEWAY_ENDPOINT
  and never serves TLS with it.
end note

== 4. Verified ==

AP -> GW : LLM request and heartbeat,\npresenting {name}-tls
GW -> AP : **POST /v1/message** delivery,\nbidirectional mTLS. **Only the Agent**\n**has this inbound edge.**
TP -> GW : LLM request and task completion,\npresenting {taskName}-tls
TP -[#B71C1C]->x GW : POST /v1/agent/heartbeat: **403**.\nTasks do not send heartbeats.
note over TP, GW #90EE90
  On every inbound mTLS call the gateway
  verifies the presented leaf against
  kaalm-ca and reads the namespace off
  the SAN. Both cert shapes carry it.
end note

== 5. Rotated ==

loop continuously, within spec.renewBefore (chart default 2160h / 720h, 90d / 30d)
  CM -> AP : Secret re-issued, kubelet\nupdates the projected volume
  AP -> AP : reload via cert-file watch
  CM -> TP : Secret re-issued, kubelet\nupdates the projected volume
  TP -> TP : HTTP client reloads via\ncert-file watch
end

== 6. Deleted ==

R -> CM : Agent deleted, or AgentTask cleaned up:\nthe ownerRef cascade-deletes the Certificate
CM -> CM : cert-manager removes the\noutput Secret in both cases

legend bottom
  **Agent:** Service DNS SANs | server auth + client auth | has a listener | inbound /v1/message edge | heartbeats
  ====
  **AgentTask:** one task.kaalm.io SAN | client auth only | no listener, no Service | no inbound edge | heartbeat 403
  ====
  Step 5 rotates the leaf only. Both workloads must also watch $KAALM_CA_CERT and rebuild both trust
  pools when the CA bundle itself changes: see CA Renewal and Re-Key.
endlegend
@enduml
